metadata.title: Piper J-3 Cub
aws::graph::propositions: Piper J-3 Cub Modern Production and Characteristics
Modernized versions of the Piper J-3 Cub are produced by Cub Crafters of Washington.
Up-engined versions of the Piper J-3 Cub are produced by Cub Crafters of Washington.
Modernized versions of the Piper J-3 Cub are produced by American Legend Aircraft in Texas.
Up-engined versions of the Piper J-3 Cub are produced by American Legend Aircraft in Texas.
Cub Crafters is a company located in Washington.
American Legend Aircraft is a company located in Texas.
The Piper J-3 Cub continues to be sought after by bush pilots for its short takeoff and landing (STOL) capabilities.
The Piper J-3 Cub continues to be sought after by recreational pilots for its nostalgia appeal.
The new aircraft produced by Cub Crafters and American Legend Aircraft are actually modeled on the PA-11.
The Legend company sells an open-cowl version with the cylinder heads exposed, like the J-3 Cub.
An electrical system is standard from both Cub Crafters and American Legend Aircraft manufacturers.
The J-3 Cub is distinguished from its successors by having a cowl that exposes its engine's cylinder heads.
The exposed cylinders of any J-3 Cub's engine were usually fitted with sheet metal "eyebrow" air scoops.
The sheet metal "eyebrow" air scoops direct air over the cylinder's fins for more effective engine cooling in flight.
Very few other examples exist of "flat" aircraft engine installations in which the cylinder heads are exposed.
"Flat" aircraft engine installations are distinct from radial engines.

text:
### Modern production
Modernized and up-engined versions are produced by Cub Crafters of Washington and by American Legend Aircraft in Texas, as the Cub continues to be sought after by bush pilots for its short takeoff and landing (STOL)  capabilities, as well as by recreational pilots for its nostalgia appeal. The new aircraft are actually modeled on the PA-11, though the Legend company does sell an open-cowl version with the cylinder heads exposed, like the J-3 Cub. An electrical system is standard from both manufacturers.

The J-3 is distinguished from its successors by having a cowl that exposes its engine's cylinder heads  the exposed cylinders of any J-3's engine were usually fitted with sheet metal "eyebrow" air scoops to direct air over the cylinder's fins for more effective engine cooling in flight. Very few other examples exist of "flat" aircraft engine installations (as opposed to radial engines) in which the cylinder heads are exposed.
